com.bigdata.rdf.graph.impl.util

Class GASRunnerBase<VS,ES,ST>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.bigdata.rdf.graph.impl.util.GASRunnerBase<VS,ES,ST>
  • Type Parameters:
    VS - The generic type for the per-vertex state. This is scoped to the computation of the IGASProgram.
    ES - The generic type for the per-edge state. This is scoped to the computation of the IGASProgram.
    ST - The generic type for the SUM. This is often directly related to the generic type for the per-edge state, but that is not always true. The SUM type is scoped to the GATHER + SUM operation (NOT the computation).
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Callable<IGASStats>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    BigdataGASRunner, RAMGASRunner, SAILGASRunner

    public abstract class GASRunnerBase<VS,ES,ST>
extends Object
implements Callable<IGASStats>
    Base class for running performance tests.
    Author:
    Bryan Thompson TODO Do we need a different driver if the algorithm always visits all vertices? For such algorithms, we just run them once per graph (unless the graph is dynamic).

    • Constructor Detail

      • GASRunnerBase

        public GASRunnerBase(String[] args)
              throws ClassNotFoundException
        Run a GAS analytic against some data set.
        Parameters:
        args - USAGE:
        (options) analyticClass propertyFile

        Where:

        propertyFile
        The implementation specific property file or other type of configuration file.
        and options are any of:
        -nthreads
        The #of threads which will be used for GATHER and SCATTER operations (default ).
        -nruns
        The #of times that the algorithm will be run. For algorithms that are initialized with a single starting vertex drawn from a random sample, total number of runs is nruns * nsamples. For algorithms that are initialize with either all vertices, there will be a total of nruns runs. (default )
        -nsamples
        For algorithms that use a single starting vertex (such as BFS, SSSP, etc.), this is the #of starting vertices that will be randomly selected. The sampled vertices will have at least one out-edge or in-edge as appropriate based on the IGASProgram. For algorithm will be run ONCE for EACH sampled vertex. This parameter is ignored for algorithms that initialize the frontier with all vertices (PR, CC, etc). (default )
        -seed
        The seed for the random number generator (default ).
        -schedulerClass
        Override the default IGASScheduler. Class must implement IGASSchedulerImpl.
        -load
        Loads the named resource IFF the KB is empty (or does not exist) at the time this utility is executed. This option may appear multiple times. The resources will be searched for as URLs, on the CLASSPATH, and in the file system.

        Throws:
        ClassNotFoundException

      • call

        public final IGASStats call()
                     throws Exception
        Run the test.

        This provides a safe pattern for either loading data into a temporary journal, which is then destroyed, or using an exiting journal and optionally loading in some data set. When we load the data the journal is destroyed afterwards and when the journal is pre-existing and we neither load the data nor destroy the journal. This has to do with the effective BufferMode (if transient) and whether the file is specified and whether a temporary file is created (CREATE_TEMP_FILE). If we do our own file create if the effective buffer mode is non-transient, then we can get all this information.

        Specified by:
        call in interface Callable<IGASStats>
        Throws:
        Exception
